snippet.textDisplay: Seeing this just warms my heart. it is not the grandest pokemon episode for me but looking at this small animation just teaches a lot of good lessons. Just like for example, Bea misunderstood about what it means to be strong, being strong doesn't mean you need to win cuz Bea really wanted to win and it just ends up making her character selfish to the extent she's being insensitive over her pokemon. But the true essence to be strong for me is to be willing to accept that you're weak or like accepting that he/she has limitations. So Bea needed to realize that she needs help together with her pokemon to overcome the trials that they're facing, and it was good thing she got to understand that in the end.

snippet.textDisplay:
English is not my first language, be indulgent, thanks!

I don't understand this story of whitewasing, for me it's just the sunlight that influences the tones of her skin. In games the notion of brightness is much less present, whether the character is in the shade or in full sun, the colors change very little, but there in the anime, if we compare the scenes in full sun, in the cave and in the rain, Bea's skin seems to be more brown than white, no? It also applies to the Nessa fanart, the artists do not use the right palette, so what? The principle of FANart is that the FAN illustrates his vision of the character, right? And then, the people who complain about this whitewashing thingy, complained more about the arts that did not use the right palette but were Nessa was still more dark red/brown than real whitewashing arts that were made for satirical purpose...

snippet.textDisplay: I have to say that I love this series!  The Pokemon anime has always been meant for little kids (and that's not a thing I would change -- except maybe getting rid of Ash, please).  These short stories involving Corviknight Taxi Guy are simple, yet so thoughtfully made.  The animation here is beautiful and dynamic, and the way the Pokemon move look amazing!  I've been a fan of Pokemon for over 20 years and am so happy to see things like this and Pokemon Generations telling far better stories than the main anime would ever show.  Keep them coming!
